aves behind natural science themes to embrace freedom, power, and history, which, McKeon argues, lay out the whole field of human action. The authors McKeon considers-Hobbes, Machiavelli, Spinoza, Kant, and J. S. Mill-show brilliantly how philosophic methods work in action, via analyses that do not merely reduce or deconstruct meaning, but enhance those texts by reconnecting them to the active history of philosophy and to problems of ethics, politics, and history. The waves of modernism and post-modernism are receding. Philosophic pluralism is now available, fully formulated, in McKeon's work, spreading from the humanities to the social sciences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aHistoryxPhilosophy. 0aLibertyxPhilosophy. 0aPower (Philosophy) 0aSocial sciencesxPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aOlson, Joanne K., eeditor.1 aOwen, David B., eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226340357423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226340357.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles